Labicana] of Labici (Liv.11 39, JV 45) or Labicum (Colomuz), an ancient city of Latium, at the north-east foot of the Alban hills, about fifteen miles south-east of Rome, west of Praeneste and north-east of Tusculum. It was a member of the Latin league, and as such retained down to a late period the right of participating in the sacrifices on the Alban Mount (Dionys. v 61). In common with Corbio and Gabii, it is frequently mentioned as a place of great importance in the history of the Aequian wars of the third and fourth centuries of the city (Liv. 11 39, Dionys.
